# Code intelligence: use grove first

This project has the **grove** MCP server — structural code tools backed by
tree-sitter. For any question about *where code is, what a file contains, or how
code connects*, prefer grove over grepping or reading whole files. grove returns
byte-precise, token-cheap answers with stable `symbol-id`s you can pass between calls.

**Reach for grove before Read/grep when the question is:**

| You want to… | Use |
|---|---|
| see what's in a file (not read all of it) | `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}outline` (add `kind=class` / `detail=0` on large files) |
| find where something is defined or used | `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}symbols`, or `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}definition` for go-to-def |
| read one function/type body | `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}source` (by id, or file+name) |
| know what calls a function | `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}callers` |
| confirm an edit didn't break syntax | `{{TOOL_PREFIX}}check` (after editing) |

These tools are deferred — load their schemas with ToolSearch up front when a code
question arrives, rather than defaulting to a search agent or grep.

Languages indexed: {{LANGS}}. (Outside these, fall back to normal tools.)
Notes: `callers`/`definition` are name-based (not receiver-type resolved); read
results with that in mind.
